Problem Statement

Given the head of a singly linked list, determine if the linked list contains a cycle.
A cycle exists if a node’s next pointer points to a previously visited node.

Example Problem:

Input: head = [3 -> 2 -> 0 -> -4], tail connects to node index 1 (2)
Output: true
Explanation: There is a cycle in the linked list.


Constraints:

Number of nodes: [0, 10^4]

Node values: -10^5 <= Node.val <= 10^5

Algorithm (Floyd’s Cycle Detection / Fast & Slow Pointers)

Initialize two pointers:

slow = head → moves 1 step at a time

fast = head → moves 2 steps at a time

Traverse the linked list:

Move slow one step and fast two steps.

If slow == fast at any point → cycle exists → return true.

If fast or fast.next becomes null → reached the end → no cycle → return false.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)

Java Code
class ListNode {
    int val;
    ListNode next;
    ListNode(int val) { this.val = val; this.next = null; }
}

public class DetectCycle {

    public static boolean hasCycle(ListNode head) {
        if (head == null || head.next == null) return false;

        ListNode slow = head;
        ListNode fast = head;

        while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {
            slow = slow.next;           // move 1 step
            fast = fast.next.next;      // move 2 steps

            if (slow == fast) {         // cycle detected
                return true;
            }
        }

        return false; // no cycle
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Example Problem
        ListNode head = new ListNode(3);
        head.next = new ListNode(2);
        head.next.next = new ListNode(0);
        head.next.next.next = new ListNode(-4);

        // Creating a cycle: tail connects to node with value 2
        head.next.next.next.next = head.next;

        System.out.println("Has Cycle: " + hasCycle(head)); // Output: true
    }
}

Code Explanation

Two-pointer technique:

slow moves 1 step at a time.

fast moves 2 steps at a time.

If there is a cycle, the fast pointer will eventually catch up with the slow pointer.

If the list ends (fast == null or fast.next == null), there is no cycle.

Dry Run (Example Problem)
Linked List: 3 -> 2 -> 0 -> -4
Cycle: tail (-4) connects to 2

Step 1: slow=3, fast=3
Step 2: slow=2, fast=0
Step 3: slow=0, fast=2
Step 4: slow=-4, fast=-4 → slow == fast → cycle detected
Output = true


Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
